Adding nanoseconds is a completely valid way of doing this. If you want a solution that is more self-explanatory, you can use [`LocalDateTime#plus(long, TemporalUnit)`][1]:

	private static final DateTimeFormatter FORMATTER = DateTimeFormatter.ofPattern(&quot;yyyy-MM-dd HH:mm:ss.SSS&quot;);

	public static void main(String[] args) {
		LocalDateTime localDateTime = LocalDateTime.parse(&quot;2022-01-01 00:00:00.123&quot;, FORMATTER);
		localDateTime = localDateTime.plus(1L, ChronoUnit.MILLIS);
        //         How much you are adding ^              ^ What you are adding

		System.out.println(FORMATTER.format(localDateTime));
	}

The [`TemporalUnit`][2] parameter explains exactly what you are adding to the the timestamp, thus making your code more easily understandable to other programmers who may be viewing it. It also takes care of the unit conversions behind the scenes, so there is less margin for human error and your code is not cluttered with math.

  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/time/LocalDateTime.html#plus-long-java.time.temporal.TemporalUnit-
  [2]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/time/temporal/TemporalUnit.html

